Business Cases are one of the core concepts of Workplace 2. This article takes a closer look at Business Cases, exploring how they are created, managed, and used within the Workplace 2 environment.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Find a Business Case
Once a Business Case has been uploaded to Workplace 2, it can be viewed in the portal interface, and actions can be performed on it.

Business Cases are displayed in tile format in two places in Workplace 2:

- **Business Cases tab:** Contains all uploaded Business Case definitions

- **Dashboard:** Provides quick access to favorited and recently opened Business Case definitions

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Finding a specific Business Case can be done in one of the following ways:

- **Global search bar:** Search for the Business Case by name or ID

> Tip: Use search prefixes

Use the prefix `id:` to search for a specific Business Case by its ID, for example `id:3048d62b-dbb7-4524-b9fd-f85f5b7d2f37`.

- **Business Cases tab:** Find the Business Case in the folder structure of the Business Cases tab

- **Dashboard:** Select a recently visited or favorited Business Case from the Dashboard tab

> Tip: Favorite Business Cases

You can pin a frequently used Business Case to your Dashboard by marking it as favorite. This can be done in one of two ways:

Click the ![](data:image/png;base64,) star icon in the Business Case tile.

- Use the **Mark as Favorite** button in the Business Case details page.

## Start a Business Case
To open a new Business Case Instance, locate the desired Business Case definition and click **Start** in the tile body. The Business Case is immediately instantiated in the background by Process Engine, and the task editor is opened at the first Human Task in the workflow.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## View the details of a Business Case
The details page of a Business Case displays information about the Business Case and action buttons to manage it. You can access it in one of the following ways:

- **Click the Business Case tile** in the Dashboard or Business Cases tab

- **Click the Business Case ID** in the Business Case Instances tab

- **Open the URL** of the Business Case

> Tip: How to get the URL of a Business Case

Every Workplace item can be accessed through a unique URL that leads to its details page. To copy the URL, open the details panel of the desired item and click the **Copy link** button.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The details page of a Business Case contains the following information:

Field

Description

**Configuration File**

Filename of the Business Case XML configuration file

**Target Folder**

Folder location of the Business Case within Workplace

**Name**

Name of the Business Case

**Summary**

*(optional)* Short description of the Business Case

**Full Description**

*(optional)* Full description of the Business Case

**Created by**

Account name of the creator of the Business Case

**Created at**

Date and time of creation

**Last updated at**

Date and time of the latest update

The following actions can be performed on a Business Case from its details page:

- **Favorite**: Mark the Business Case as a favorite. It will be displayed on the Dashboard

- **Edit**: Opens the configuration window of the Business Case

- **Delete**: Deletes the Business Case

- **Copy link**: Copies the URL of the Business Case to the clipboard

- **Start**: Start the Business Case

### FAQ
#### What is the difference between a Business Case and a Business Case Instance?
Business Cases are definitions of interactive processes. Once a Business Case has been started, it becomes a Business Case Instance and receives a unique ID. Several Business Case Instances can be instantiated from the same Business Case definition and can run simultaneously.

#### What is the difference between a Business Case and any other IPD process?
Business Cases are a specific form of processes. Like other processes, they are saved in IPD format and are executed behind the scenes by Process Engine. The distinguishing factor is the use of special process elements called Human Tasks. These are touchpoints between the user and Process Engine which require some form of input, for example selecting a document template or sending an email.
